1.1   Sectional Nomenclature
Rectangle 2
Sectioning produces a 2D representation of a 3D structure.

It shows ONLY the structures that are IN the plane of section.
Structures outside the plane of section are NOT seen.

Frontal or coronal plane
separates the body into anterior and posterior portions.
The coronal plane is oriented parallel to long axis of the body.
Picture 2

Remember, halves, by definition are equal in size.
Therefore, there is only ONE midsagittal plane in the body.
halves
Marker
There are an infinite number of parasagittal sections in the body.
parasagittal sections
Marker

Sagittal plane
separates the body into right and left portions. 
A midsagittal section passes through the midline, dividing the body into right and left halves     .
A parasagittal section misses the midline, creating right and left portions of unequal size     .
The sagittal plane is oriented parallel to the long axis of the body

Transverse or cross-sectional plane 
The transverse plane is oriented perpendicular to the long axis of the body
separates the body into superior and inferior portions.
in humans, is equivalent to the horizontal plane
